name: To Kill a Mockingbird
author: Harper Lee
summary: The unforgettable novel of a childhood in a sleepy Southern town and the crisis of conscience that rocked it.

author: George Orwell
summary: A dystopian novel set in a future totalitarian society where the government has complete control over every aspect of citizens lives.

name: Pride and Prejudice
author: Jane Austen
summary: A romantic novel following the emotional development of Elizabeth Bennet, who learns the error of making hasty judgments and comes to appreciate the difference between the superficial and the essential.

name: The Great Gatsby
author: F. Scott Fitzgerald
summary: A novel set in the summer of 1922, following the life of millionaire Jay Gatsby as he tries to win back his former love Daisy Buchanan.

name: One Hundred Years of Solitude
author: Gabriel García Márquez
summary: A novel that tells the multi-generational story of the Buendía family, whose patriarch, José Arcadio Buendía, founded the town of Macondo.

name: Invisible Man
author: Ralph Ellison
summary: A novel that addresses many of the social and intellectual issues facing African Americans in the early twentieth century.

name: Beloved
author: Toni Morrison
summary: A novel inspired by the life of Margaret Garner, an African American who escaped slavery in Kentucky in late January 1856 by crossing the Ohio River to Ohio, a free state.

name: The Catcher in the Rye
author: J. D. Salinger
summary: A novel about a teenage boy named Holden Caulfield who is expelled from prep school and wanders around New York City for a few days before returning home.

name: To the Lighthouse
author: Virginia Woolf
summary: A novel that centers on the Ramsay family and their visits to the Isle of Skye in Scotland between 1910 and 1920.

name: Jane Eyre
author: Charlotte Brontë
summary: A novel that follows the experiences of its eponymous heroine, including her growth to adulthood and her love for Mr. Rochester, the brooding master of Thornfield Hall.
